    "code": "I10",
    "rawCode": "I10",
    "shortDesc": "Essential (primary) hypertension",
    "longDesc": "Essential (primary) hypertension",
    "plainEnglish": "Essential hypertension, commonly called high blood pressure, is a condition where the force of blood pushing against your artery walls is consistently too high (140/90 mmHg or higher). In most cases, doctors cannot identify a specific cause—it develops gradually over time due to factors like genetics, age, obesity, stress, and salt intake. You may not feel any symptoms at all, but over time high blood pressure can damage your heart, kidneys, and blood vessels, increasing your risk of heart attack and stroke.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, cardiologists, internal medicine doctors, and nurses regularly use this code to monitor and treat hypertension in routine office visits and preventive care. It commonly appears on EOB statements as one of the most frequently billed diagnoses in healthcare, often assigned when patients have blood pressure checks or medication management appointments.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
