    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means that high blood pressure has caused structural changes or damage to the heart muscle and its function, but the heart is still able to pump blood adequately without failing. Over time, chronic high blood pressure forces the heart to work harder, causing the heart muscle to thicken and become less flexible, which can lead to problems like irregular heartbeats or reduced blood flow to the heart itself.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, internists, and primary care physicians use this code when managing patients with long-standing hypertension who show signs of heart damage (often detected on EKG or echocardiogram) but have not yet progressed to heart failure. This code frequently appears on patient EOBs and is important for documenting the complications of untreated or poorly controlled high blood pressure.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
    "chapterId": 9,
