    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a heart attack where the specific location or type of heart damage hasn't been clearly identified or specified. A heart attack happens when blood flow to part of the heart muscle is suddenly blocked (usually by a blood clot in a coronary artery), causing that part of the heart to be deprived of oxygen and become damaged. Symptoms typically include chest pain or pressure, shortness of breath, and sometimes pain radiating to the arm, neck, or jaw.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists use this code when a patient is diagnosed with an acute heart attack but the exact location or type hasn't been determined yet, often during initial emergency assessment. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients admitted with acute chest pain and elevated cardiac markers, though more specific codes (identifying anterior, inferior, lateral, or posterior wall involvement) are typically assigned once diagnostic testing like EKG or echocardiogram clarifies the damage location.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
    "chapterId": 9,
