    "code": "I27.20",
    "rawCode": "I2720",
    "shortDesc": "Pulmonary hypertension, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Pulmonary hypertension, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Pulmonary hypertension means the blood pressure in the arteries of your lungs is abnormally high, forcing your heart to work much harder to pump blood through them. This can develop for many different reasons (such as chronic lung disease, heart disease, or blood clots), but in this case, the specific cause hasn't been identified or documented. Over time, high pressure in the lungs can weaken the right side of your heart and lead to shortness of breath, fatigue, chest pain, and swelling in the legs.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, cardiologists, and internists commonly use this code when a patient presents with elevated lung blood pressure but the underlying cause remains unclear or unspecified. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing cardiac imaging, echocardiograms, or right heart catheterization to evaluate persistent shortness of breath or heart problems.",
