    "shortDesc": "Atrioventricular block, complete",
    "longDesc": "Atrioventricular block, complete",
    "plainEnglish": "Complete atrioventricular block (also called third-degree heart block) means the electrical signal that tells your heart to beat cannot get from the upper chambers (atria) to the lower chambers (ventricles), so they beat independently of each other at different rates. This happens when the electrical \"wiring\" in your heart is damaged or blocked, and can cause symptoms like dizziness, fainting, shortness of breath, or chest discomfort because your heart isn't pumping blood effectively.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists and electrophysiologists use this code when diagnosing patients with severe conduction problems, typically identified on an EKG or cardiac monitor. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients requiring hospitalization, pacemaker placement, or emergency intervention, as complete heart block is a serious condition requiring immediate medical attention.",
